===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₃reǵ-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|right}}, {{m|enm|riȝt}}, {{m|enm|reȝt}}, from {{inh|en|ang|riht}}, {{m|ang|ryht}}, {{m|ang|reht|t=right}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*reht}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*rehtaz|t=right, direct}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*h₃reǵtós|t=having moved in a straight line}}, from {{m|ine-pro|*h₃reǵ-|t=to straighten, direct}}. An Indo-European past participle, it became a Germanic adjective which has been used also as a noun since the common Germanic period. Cognate with {{cog|fy|rjocht}}, {{cog|nl|recht}}, {{cog|de|recht}} and {{m|de|Recht}}, {{cog|sv|rätt}} and {{m|sv|rät}}, {{cog|da|ret}}, {{cog|nb|rett}}, {{cog|nn|rett}}, and {{cog|is|rétt}}. The Indo-European root is also the source of {{cog|grc|ὀρεκτός}} and {{cog|la|rēctus}}; {{cog|sq|drejt}} was borrowed from Latin.

